04817nam a22007695i 9781400885312DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2017    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008853127 a10.1515/97814008853122doi  a(DE-B1597)479687  a(OCoLC)980845341  a(OCoLC)984686497  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDT97b.M4 2018 7aHIS0090002bisacsh 7aHIS0370002bisacsh 7aHIS0550002bisacsh 7aPOL0310002bisacsh04a962.030899272231 aMestyan, Adam, eauthor.10aArab Patriotism :bThe Ideology and Culture of Power in Late Ottoman Egypt /cAdam Mestyan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b12 halftones. 8 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tTables -- tNotes on Transliteration, Names, Titles, and Currency -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: The Making of the Khedivate -- t1. The Ottoman Origins of Arab Patriotism -- t2. The Ottoman Legitimation of Power: The Khedivate -- t3. The European Aesthetics of Khedivial Power -- tPart II: "A Garden with Mellow Fruits of Refinement" -- t4. A Gentle Revolution -- t5. Constitutionalism and Revolution: The Arab Opera -- tPart III: The Reinvention of the Khedivate -- t6. Hārūn al- Rashīd under Occupation -- t7. Behind the Scenes: A Committee and the Law, 1880s- 1900s -- t8. Distinction: Muṣṭafā Kāmil and the Making of an Arab Prince -- tConclusion: The Ottoman Origin of Arab Nationalisms -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex  aArab Patriotism presents the essential backstory to the formation of the modern nation-state and mass nationalism in the Middle East. While standard histories claim that the roots of Arab nationalism emerged in opposition to the Ottoman milieu, Adam Mestyan points to the patriotic sentiment that grew in the Egyptian province of the Ottoman Empire during the nineteenth century, arguing that it served as a pivotal way station on the path to the birth of Arab nationhood.Through extensive archival research, Mestyan examines the collusion of various Ottoman elites in creating this nascent sense of national belonging and finds that learned culture played a central role in this development. Mestyan investigates the experience of community during this period, engendered through participation in public rituals and being part of a theater audience. He describes the embodied and textual ways these experiences were produced through urban spaces, poetry, performances, and journals. From the Khedivial Opera House's staging of Verdi's Aida and the first Arabic magazine to the 'Urabi revolution and the restoration of the authority of Ottoman viceroys under British occupation, Mestyan illuminates the cultural dynamics of a regime that served as the precondition for nation-building in the Middle East.A wholly original exploration of Egypt in the context of the Ottoman Empire, Arab Patriotism sheds fresh light on the evolving sense of political belonging in the Arab world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aArabszEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 0aPatriotismzEgyptxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Egypt (see also Ancient / Egypt).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054332240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400885312zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400885312.jpg  a978-3-11-054332-2  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL